The head of the White House will arrive in the Norwegian capital in the morning with his wife Michelle and will be busy.
He will first visit the Nobel Institute, where he will meet for the first time with five members of a committee selected in October from 172 people and 33 organizations.
The presidential couple then has a meeting with King Harald V of Norway and Queen Sonja.
In the afternoon, the visit will culminate in a ceremony at which Obama will receive the prestigious award.
He will receive it as the fourth American president, but only the third, who will receive the award directly in office.
The White House has already announced that Obama will talk about the Afghan war at the award ceremony.
The president does not want to avoid this topic, because he realizes that he is accepting the award as the president who is currently at war in two countries.
He stepped up his war effort a few days ago by sending more troops to Afghanistan, which will not forget to emphasize any of his critics.
During the ceremony, Obama will also receive a gold medal, a diploma and a check for ten million Swedish crowns (about 24 million Czech crowns).
He intends to give them to charity, but he has not yet decided on a specific charity.
The busy program will then take the president and his wife to a banquet, where, in addition to the Norwegian king and queen, there will also be a prime minister and another 250 invited guests.
From the beginning, Obama was more reticent about the price.
He said, for example, that he felt he did not fully deserve it.
He also repeated several times that it was not just a price for him, but for all those who strive for the same values as him.
He said immediately after the announcement that it was a &quot;call to action&quot; for him.
