USA: Repetition is the mother of wisdom
It is comical with what schooling effort Barack Obama, a president with a reputation for being the smartest, repeats the strategy of his predecessor, whom he considered the stupidest, on the Afghan question.
When he finally sweated his long-awaited Afghan doctrine, he turned out to have copied it through a copier from Bush&#39;s Iraq script three years ago.
Not only does he use the phrase &quot;as in Iraq&quot; several times in the text itself, but he did not even hesitate to use the title of the Bush Declaration of January 2007 as the title of his own declaration: &quot;A New Way Forward.&quot;
At the same time, three years ago, he himself criticized Bush&#39;s idea of sending fresh military reinforcements to a war-torn Iraq as an &quot;irresponsible and, as a result, catastrophic decision.&quot;
Subsequent months, however, have shown that Bush&#39;s strategy based on field commanders&#39; recommendations was the only one possible and very successful, so much so that there is no talk of Iraq at all today.
It did not improve Bush&#39;s reputation, but he objectively left his successor a much more grateful starting point than might be expected.
In Afghanistan, Barack Obama hopes the miracle will happen again.
He was again asked to increase the military contingent by field commanders, especially the commander-in-chief of the Afghan operation, General Stanley McCristal, who, despite his subordinating habits, harshly criticized the hesitant White House gunners.
He asked 40,000 men to break the situation for the better.
The president hesitated for three months, but came up with nothing better, so at least he cheated the general by 10,000 soldiers.
He was able to squeeze the promise of another 5,000 from Europe, even though he himself originally counted on at least 10.
The most problematic of Obama&#39;s entire strategy seems to be his intention to begin withdrawing troops from Afghanistan in 18 months and to complete the process within three years. The whole Obama doctrine raises more questions than it answers.
Many doubt that the half-increase will bear the same fruit as the move in Iraq.
Despite the fratricidal wars of recent years, Iraqi society is relatively well-organized, with leaders honoring the deal.
The Afghan situation is characterized by the opposite symptom - no one can be relied on and no agreements are being honored.
Under these conditions, the Afghan security forces are accustomed to changing their lord every day according to their needs.
Political institutions, even if they are formally established, will remain a small village, beyond which patriarchal tribal relations will continue to flourish.
Balancing the interests of different ethnic groups is extremely difficult due to the lack of clarity, which further complicates Pakistani and Iranian influences.
Even the building of an &quot;actionable state&quot;, which is the minimalist goal of the whole operation, does not seem very realistic.
The time horizon of Obama&#39;s strategy strikes with his voluntarism.
The situation in Afghanistan has only worsened over the last eight years and is now on the verge of an explosion.
Only a truly romantic soul, untouched by reality, can believe that soldiers sent into the turmoil of war for the purpose of &quot;returning home early&quot; will cause a miracle to be done here.
From a political point of view, setting a date for the withdrawal of troops is pure irresponsibility, as the Taliban will see this as an indirect acknowledgment of the American defeat.
The latest NATO summit showed that the willingness of Europeans to take part in combat operations in Afghanistan is coming to a loss.
European politicians cannot and do not want to explain to their constituents how the security of Germany or Italy is related to the war in the foothills of the Hindu Kush.
Another factor capable of radically intervening in the situation is the development of events around Iran.
If the situation continues to deteriorate and the intensified sanctions do not affect Iranians, the United States will have the difficult question of not trying to solve the problem by military force.
It will have to be answered at a time when, according to Obama, America is embarking on a victorious withdrawal from Afghanistan.
However, any such solution will also mean a dramatic turnaround in the Afghan situation.
The only patch for Barack Obama is the fact that there are three years left in the presidential election, and therefore there is still time left to come up with another strategy if it proves to be a total failure.
