Czech discovery: a substance that also targets &#39;hardened&#39; HIV viruses
A team of Czech and German scientists is testing new compounds that can slow down the spread of HIV in the body.
The main advantage of the improved substance is that it also targets viruses that have already acquired immunity to drugs.
In some cases, this fact outweighs the fact that the compound does not act as strongly on a common variant of the virus as some of the drugs already available.
AIDS cannot yet be cured.
However, a mixture of drugs that prevent the spread of HIV in the body can significantly prolong patients&#39; lives.
However, their use is accompanied by a number of side effects.
In addition, incomplete suppression of virus replication results in the development of so-called resistant viruses, against which drugs are no longer effective.
The work of experts from three institutes of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic, the Institute of Chemical Technology in Prague and the University of Heidelberg opens the way to deal with virus resistance.
They have shown that substances called metallocarboranes act on the protein responsible for the reproduction of the HIV virus.
Metallocarboranes are compounds of boron, hydrogen, carbon and cobalt.
These compounds block the spread of the virus differently than all drugs used today, and therefore can overcome the problem of resistance.
In their work, researchers come up with new &#39;improved&#39; compounds prepared based on knowledge of the molecular mechanism of their binding to the viral protein.
Metallocarboranes have a unique three-dimensional structure: two multi-walled cages made up of boron, hydrogen and carbon atoms are connected by a metal atom, in this case cobalt.
A treacherous and resistant virus
The HIV protease is a protein of the HIV virus that is essential for the life cycle of the virus.
Without HIV protease-induced cleavage of HIV, mature infectious virus particles would not be formed.
When we stop the HIV protease, we also stop the spread of the virus in the patient&#39;s body, the researchers explain in a press release issued by the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry of the Academy of Sciences of the Czech Republic.
In a paper published in the Journal of Medicinal Chemistry, researchers describe a series of compounds in which two pairs of cages (see table) are connected by a short organic chain, which is further systematically modified.
Slightly weaker, but more reliable
The effect of this series of substances against HIV protease was tested in a test tube and also against its resistant variants obtained from HIV-infected patients.
The effect of metallocarboranes on a common variant of the enzyme is not as strong as that of clinically used drugs, but it does not lose its effect for resistant variants against which the drugs used are often ineffective.
The unique mechanism of action as well as their other properties such as biological and chemical stability, low toxicity and the possibility of further chemical modifications make metallocarboranes interesting compounds for further research aimed at designing effective drugs against HIV, says Pavlína Řezáčová, head of the Structural Biology Laboratory of the Institute of Organic Chemistry and Biochemistry and the Institute of Molecular Genetics of the Academy of Sciences.
