New vaccination
Free vaccines for August children
From January, children born last August 2 and later can be vaccinated against pneumococci free of charge.
The condition is that they have not yet received a single dose of vaccination.
Anyone who started vaccinating last year or earlier must pay for another revaccination.
The first dose of vaccination must be given between 3 and 5 months of age.
Already last year, a quarter of families voluntarily had their children vaccinated against pneumococci.
At the same time, the parents paid 1,600 crowns for one dose or more.
Four doses are needed to vaccinate the youngest children.
Overall, experts estimate that health insurance companies spend 300 to 450 thousand crowns a year on vaccination benefits.
But it will save on the treatment that children would need without vaccinations.
So far, the state has paid about 500,000 a year for all vaccinations of children.
Paid vaccination was introduced by the so-called Janot package.
Pneumococcus causes inflammation of the middle ear, but also serious infections, including meningitis and blood poisoning.
According to a survey in hospitals, up to 28 children under the age of 10 die from pneumococcal infections in our country every year.
In addition to the Czech Republic, they have introduced paid vaccination of children against pneumococci in about 40 countries.
Will vaccination be mandatory?
At the same time, however, there are opinions that this vaccination may be mandatory in the future.
From January, it is to be paid by insurance companies and optional.
Rudolf Kalovský, the head of the Nahlas civic association, suggested, for example, that compulsory vaccination would be better.
His association has long promoted the pneumococcal vaccine.
The experts at the international conference that our association attended were not completely satisfied with the fact that we have voluntary vaccinations.
It&#39;s not perfect.
On the other hand, we are glad that at least this has been achieved.
I think that is the path we must take now, said Kalovský.
However, the Ministry of Health does not want to change the procedure of vaccination against pneumococci.
We are not thinking about it at the moment, said his spokesman Vlastimil Sršeň.
Voluntary vaccination has its drawbacks, doctors say
The chairwoman of the Professional Society of General Practitioners of Pediatricians, Hana Cabrnochová, acknowledges that voluntary vaccination has its disadvantages.
If all children were vaccinated, a reduction in the number of revaccinations could be considered. &quot;In a situation where this vaccine costs such a large amount, we quite understand the political decision that vaccination was started as voluntary,&quot; says Cabrnoch.
Experts expect more than 80 percent of new parents to have their infants vaccinated against pneumococci from next year.
Vaccination against pneumococci is also groundbreaking in that it is paid for by health insurance companies, not the state, as the first comprehensive vaccination of children.
Insurance companies should spend money on prevention, thus saving on further treatment, explains Cabrnoch.
Doctors will have to buy the substances themselves
But there are concerns for GPs about buying vaccines.
According to the original intention, vaccines were to be bought by insurance companies and doctors would receive them in the same way as the state supplies them with substances for other vaccinations.
However, some MEPs feared that insurance companies could &quot;withdraw money from health insurance&quot;.
Doctors will therefore have to buy the substances and wait for the insurance companies to reimburse them.
It is estimated that individual GPs will invest 40,000 a month in vaccines, a significant amount.
It won&#39;t be easy at all, says Cabrnoch.
