Turkish justice has dissolved the Kurdish party, and the decision has serious consequences.
The Turkish Constitutional Court on Friday ruled to abolish the country&#39;s main pro-Kurdish party. The decision immediately sparked protests and demonstrations in the Kurdish community in the south-east of the country and in Istanbul.
This decision can greatly complicate the task of the government, which is trying to lend a friendly hand to the Kurdish community and try to end 25 years of conflict.
The Democratic Society Party (DTP) was dissolved because it became &quot;a nest of activities that threaten the independence of the state and its indivisible unity,&quot; Supreme Court President Hasim Kilic told reporters after four days of talks.
The decision was taken unanimously by 11 judges, requiring a seven-majority majority to dissolve the party, Kiliç said, adding that 37 party cadres, including its president Ahmet Türk and MP Aysela Tugluk, were banned from participating in political life for five years.
The judge also announced the lifting of the parliamentary immunity enjoyed by Mr Türk and Ms Tugluk and the confiscation of the party&#39;s assets by the Ministry of Finance.
The DTP has 21 seats in Parliament (out of 500).
Even before the verdict, the party leadership pointed out that deputies would rather leave Parliament than act as non-political deputies.
The decision is a follow-up to a 2007 trial by Abdurrahman Yalcinkay, the prosecutor of the Court of Cassation, who accuses the DTP of obeying the &quot;orders&quot; of the Kurdistan Workers&#39; Party (PKK), which Ankara and many countries consider a terrorist organization.
Many observers believe that the DTP is a legal political showcase for the PKK rebels.
The party assures it that it has no &quot;basic connection&quot; with the PKK, but refuses to label it a terrorist organization and calls on the government to negotiate with it.
The court&#39;s verdict comes at a time when the government is giving a friendly hand to the Kurdish community, offering a series of measures to strengthen their rights and trying to reduce Kurdish support for the PKK and end the conflict.
The DTP leadership confirmed that the dissolution of the party could lead to renewed tensions in southeastern Anatolia, where many demonstrations against the conditions under which PKK leader Abdullah Öcalan is being held in clashes with police have collapsed in recent weeks.
Since the announcement of the justice decision, thousands of protesters have gathered in front of the DTP headquarters in Diyarbakir, a large city in the southeast inhabited mainly by Kurds.
Police used tear gas grenades and water cannons, while protesters threw Molotov cocktails or fired slingshot stones.
About a hundred people also demonstrated in Istanbul.
After the verdict, Mr. Türk said that the decision of justice would only &quot;deepen despair&quot;.
Turkey cannot solve this issue by banning the party, the press said.
The government, made up of a party from the Islamist movement, also condemned the decision.
We are fundamentally against party interference.
It doesn&#39;t solve anything, said Energy Minister Taner Yildiz.
This decision is a complete blow to the democratic proposals launched by the government, commented political scientist Ahmet Insel.
Of course, we can expect a response from the PKK, he added.
On Thursday, the PKK claimed responsibility for one of the deadliest attacks in northern Turkey, which killed seven soldiers three days earlier.
