Cradle of dinosaurs
Tawa hallae looked like many other carnivorous dinosaurs: The animal, two meters long and 1.50 meters high, ran on two strong hind limbs, had an elongated skull with sharp, curved teeth, short forelegs with sickle claws and a long tail.
If this species lived a few million years later, there would be nothing extraordinary.
Sterling Nesbitt of the University of Texas at Austin and colleagues write in Thursday&#39;s issue of the journal Science that Tawa hallae was one of the first dinosaurs to have these physical traits.
The animal lived about 215 million years ago in present-day New Mexico, which was then located in the equatorial arid region of the Pangea supercontinent.
Tawa opens a new window to the earlier evolution of dinosaurs, says Nesbitt.
It shows us a lot about the kinship, distribution and features of early dinosaurs.
In 2006, Nesbitt and other paleontologists began excavations at Ghost Ranch in northern New Mexico.
Sometimes we found a dozen dinosaur bones in one day, unprecedented for Triassic sediments, according to team member Randall Irmis of the Museum of Natural History in Utah.
Some of the bones were quickly identified by scientists as a new species.
During the excavations, they collected the remains of a total of five individuals.
The finding is confirmed by theories about the early history of dinosaurs.
The name &quot;Tawa&quot; comes from the sun god of the Hopi Indians.
This is an unusual finding for Sterling Nesbitt: &quot;Triassic dinosaur fossils are very rare, usually only single fragments can be found.&quot;
Other dinosaur experts do not share this enthusiasm without reservation.
This finding is not particularly sensational, but it confirms some theories about the early history of dinosaurs, says Martin Sander from the University of Bonn.
According to current scientific opinion, dinosaurs first appeared about 230 million years ago.
However, many of the oldest fossils are not complete, so the assignment of pradinosaurs is usually controversial.
Experts discuss, for example, when lizards split into three most important lineages: carnivorous theropods, which later included Tyranosaurus rex, Velociraptor, as well as birds, &quot;long-necked&quot; four-legged sauropods and their relatives, and the herbivores Ornithischia (bird&#39;s-footed gulls), which included for example Triceratops and Stegosaurus species.
Tawa hallae is, after the analysis of Nesbitt and his colleagues, the original therapod.
It has an interesting combination of primitive and advanced qualities, says Nesbitt.
On the skull of Tawa hallae, researchers found, for example, evidence of air sacs that even the descendants of theropods have birds.
Thanks to air bags, the breathing of birds is more efficient than that of mammals.
In Tawa hallae, the bones of the spine were apparently partially filled with air.
Tawa is the oldest and most primitive teropod with air bags, says Randall Irmis.
As a related line of giant sauropods later also had air sacs and light bones, this useful innovation probably already formed a common ancestor between the two groups.
At least three waves of migration to North America
Because the most primitive dinosaurs known to date lived in South America, scientists concluded that lizards first appeared there.
According to this, the three lines of development soon split and spread from South America to all continents, which at the time, as the Pangea supercontinent, formed a uniform land mass.
The fact that the team, together with Tawa hallae, found the remains of two other, not particularly closely related theropods, would also support this.
The three cannot come from one common, immigrant ancestor, scientists argue.
We believe there have been at least three waves of migration to North America, says Alan Turner of the American Museum of Natural History in New York, co-author of the scientific study.
Of course, there are also contradictions.
One even older species, Silesaurus, which belongs to the group of the heaviest dinosaurs, lived in today&#39;s Poland, says Bonn paleontologist Martin Sander.
His assumption could put together a distorted picture, because many primitive dinosaur fossils have been preserved in South America, and are rarely found on other continents.
As dinosaurs have shown that they evolved from a relatively rare lineage of the genus of reptiles to the ruling vertebrates on earth in the Middle Ages remains an enigma.
During the Triassic, dinosaurs shared their habitat with many other reptiles, such as the ancestors of today&#39;s crocodiles and flying lizards and countless other lizards.
Around the end of the Triassic, dinosaurs spread throughout the world and many new species evolved, while relatives became extinct and the Triassic-Jurassic interface.
The success story did not last forever
There are two hypotheses to explain this change, says Martin Sander.
There may have been a mass extinction that the dinosaurs accidentally survived, but the reptiles did not.
Or the dinosaurs adapted better so they could squeeze out the competition.
In any case, the success story did not last forever.
150 million years later, a meteorite impact helped another group of animals, which also evolved into the Triassic and have lived in the shadows ever since: mammals.
