The affected person is unable to distinguish the important from the unimportant, the brain cannot filter out interfering signals, consciousness is flooded with impressions.
Like a dream, psychosis opens the floodgates to a flood of thoughts and fantasies that come from the deepest layers of consciousness.
The perception of reality in psychosis is centered, says Professor Thomas Fuchs, chief physician of the Department of General Psychiatry at the University Clinic in Heidelberg.
Schizophrenic is at the center of things, everything has a meaning directed at him.
At the same time, he gets into a passive role, becomes, like in a dream, overwhelmed by events and cannot actively shape them.
Therefore, schizophrenics often feel threatened, controlled and manipulated.
Comparison with reality is usually not possible for them, ghosts are a terrible fact, awakening is ruled out.
Experience hallucinations once in a lifetime
Other than in a dream, says Fuchss, &quot;but the sensory and spatial structure of reality, which one perceives in psychosis, remains fundamentally preserved.&quot;
Misleading thoughts and hallucinations are based on reality, the alienation of the experience takes place in a real framework.
Scientists are still faced with the puzzle of why exactly our brains do such throws.
Exceptional conditions can lead to a person&#39;s loss of relationship to reality in the short term, says Fuchs.
But not everyone develops into psychosis.
There appears to be a genetic predisposition to schizophrenia, but studies in twins have shown that genes are not the only determining factor.
Researchers believe that people with minimal brain damage.
We believe that at an early stage of development, neuronal maturation of the brain will be damaged, for example by a viral disease of the mother during pregnancy, Fuchs explains.
However, it remains a riddle how the neuronal system will fail, which has not manifested itself in many years.
Environmental influences also play a role - stress or traumatic experiences can be the initiator of psychosis, if available.
Hallucinogenic drugs can also trigger psychosis because they interfere with the transmission system.
When our brain boils
It&#39;s crazy that psychotronics suffer from their hallucinations and swallow expensive drugs to get rid of them, others give money for drugs to get them, says psychology professor Erich Kasten of Lübeck.
Whether we perceive delusions as pleasant or unpleasant is often just a matter of attitude.
Kasten has been collecting reports of hallucinations and delusions for ten years, and last year he interpreted his results in the book &quot;Die irreale Welt in unserem Kopf&quot; (The Unreal World in Our Heads).
Hallucinations are one of the typical accompanying phenomena of psychosis, but also one of the surprisingly many other diseases.
In addition to mental disorders such as borderline personality or depression, there are also often diseases such as migraine, epilepsy, multiple sclerosis or Alzheimer&#39;s or brain trauma.
Surprisingly, under certain conditions, the brain of a healthy person also hallucinates.
Hallucinations, according to Kasten, consist of the contents of thoughts that are normally suppressed.
They occur when the parts of the brain in which sensory perception is processed are too active or little suppressed; when our brain boils, or when stimulation is lacking.
Drugs can trigger this condition as well as brain damage or psychosis.
But also withdrawal of stimuli, stress, worries about love or other exceptional conditions.
In more recent studies, up to a third of respondents have reported hallucinations at least once in their lives.
In the summer of 2005, Sarah K. is 16 years old, lives in a small town in Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania and attends a grammar school there.
Actually, a completely normal girl.
If it weren&#39;t for the shapes and voices.
Breaks can appeal to her with long, dark hair.
