This shy girl is considered a tense dreamer, but Sarah K. doesn&#39;t, she knows.
He is awake, he hears and sees the boy, just as he hears and sees the girl sitting next to him on the bench.
He can even feel his presence, at least for a few moments.
It&#39;s a nice feeling, she likes the boy.
Am I crazy? He asks sometimes.
But he knows that this boy and other delusions are not real and will disappear again.
At night, the phenomena are rather depressing
Delusions are often a burden.
When she sits in the classroom, she can&#39;t watch the lessons many times because the teacher is introducing a new classmate in her eyes and ears, but he explains the math equations audibly and visibly to everyone else on the board.
At night, the phenomena are rather depressing.
As she waits in her dark room for sleep that rarely and too late arrives, she often can&#39;t tell if she&#39;s awake or asleep, if the images she sees, grimaces, or a girl with bleeding cuts on her arms and legs are created in front of her open ones. or with eyes closed.
Leave me alone, shouting at the characters.
She doesn&#39;t tell her parents or friends about it, they&#39;d think she&#39;s crazy.
Autumn 2009. Sarah K. is 20 years old today.
She graduated last year and lives with her boyfriend.
A year ago, the hallucinations stopped.
Ever since she contacted psychologist Kasten on the Internet, she knows exactly that she hasn&#39;t gone crazy.
Delusions are also an art of despair
If someone is socially isolated or their stimuli are taken away, they will most likely have hallucinations, says Kasten.
I think the brain doesn&#39;t have enough jobs and takes care of its own entertainment.
Sarah K., an only child, was afraid of other children as a little girl, often playing alone.
Her hallucinations began when she learned at 13 that the man her father had called since she had been thinking was not her own father.
Because the same brain areas are active in visual and acoustic hallucinations, which also process real perceptions and sounds, it is difficult for people with disabilities like Sarah K. to distinguish between delusions and reality. &quot;Every experience,&quot; says Kasten, &quot;takes place in the brain, and reality is also displayed there.
Hallucinations are also images that the brain creates, which is why it looks so real. &quot;
Kasten also evaluates night dreams as a form of hallucination.
Hallucinations of healthy people are not fundamentally different from hallucinations in acute psychosis.
Unlike schizophrenics, mentally healthy people are able to identify their delusions as unrealistic.
Kasten therefore advises his patients to rate hallucinations as an extraordinary ability.
Border state between dream and hallucination
Unfortunately, in our world of over-awareness, the imaginary experience is mostly pathologized, says Michael Schmidt-Degenhard, a professor in Heidelberg and chief physician of the Psychiatric and Psychotherapeutic Clinic of Florence-Nightingale Hospital in Düsseldorf.
Psychosis is a serious, painful disease, but it also brings positives, creativity - delusion is also an art of despair.
Schmidt-Degenhard studied the so-called one-in-one form of experience, a special form of altered consciousness for a dream.
Oneiroid states are highly complex, detailed fictitious dreams that the person in question considers real and cannot even distinguish them retrospectively from the waking state.
One-state state of consciousness arises in extreme situations caused by trauma or illness, such as patients with polyradicular inflammation who experience motor paralysis when fully conscious.
When a person is threatened by the loss of the world and himself, for example by a lasting, complete inability to move, he replaces life-threatening real situations with his own, imaginary world, which is disconnected from reality, says Schmidt-Degenhard.
The type of boundary between dream and hallucination.
Because it is not possible to manage a situation in reality, worlds will change, but the real situation will be presented in the imagination.
An intense form of support for the senses and the transfer of the senses in some unbearable situation, which allows us humans our own ability to form, to pass in an instant into loss of consciousness.
Everything is real, even later in the memories
Art historian Peter Cornelius Claussen also describes his one-on-one experiences in his book &quot;Herzwechsel&quot; (Heart Exchange) as a soul salvation.
He was 49 years old when, after heart valve surgery followed by a heart transplant, his consciousness embarked on a journey of several days, with his body lying motionless in the intensive care unit.
Claussen immersed himself in the world he had created, visiting foreign times and places: He became an old man bedridden, in a train sanatorium, a robot guarding his health.
He lives in the early Middle Ages among the nobility, which produces narcotics from the blood.
A Greek kidnaps him on his motorcycle to his homeland, surfs on a hospital bed in the Alps on a hospital bed and meets a Korean mobster.
He immerses himself completely in the imaginary story, everything is real, even later in his memories.
For Claussen, these inner paths are fundamentally different from any dream.
A dream is a different state, it describes your experience.
In contrast to dreams, the memories of those mental journeys are still clear after years and in insignificant details.
Even brighter and more intense than the real experience.
The intensity of this experience breaks the horizon of our other true experiences, says psychiatrist Schmidt-Degenhard.
After all, one-in-one states, psychoses, hallucinations, and drug intoxication show how fragile our inner images of external reality are, even in the waking state.
Every change in the state of consciousness, sums up by psychologist Kasten, &quot;can lead to a deformation of what we call reality.&quot;
A fact that can also be enriching.
