The auxiliary system for the parking brake is already mandatory.
As in the case of the anti-lock braking system ABS, it will also be with ESP stability control, parking brake auxiliary systems, all of which will become mandatory equipment of European cars.
In fact, it is already part of the mandatory equipment of all newly registered passenger cars and light commercial vehicles, while the others have a deadline for eliminating the shortcoming, which is February 2011.
The measure introduced in the EU aims to increase pedestrian protection, while working in such a way that it can help prevent many collisions.
The parking brake assist system increases the pressure on the brakes in an emergency, which the system detects when the driver depresses.
But he is not always able to maintain this pressure until the end.
According to a study by automotive parts maker Bosch, a third of drivers who have an accident did not apply the brake before a collision and half did not make full use of the brake force.
Up to 1,100 accidents
On the contrary, this assistance requires the maximum from the braking system, shortens the braking distance of the vehicle.
According to a study carried out in the EU alone, if all vehicles were equipped with this type of equipment, up to 1,100 pedestrian fatalities per year could be avoided.
Reducing this number will be even more pronounced - according to calculations it would prevent one in four accidents with an impact on people - after the introduction of so-called intelligent handbrake systems.
In this case, the vehicles will be equipped with a system that (using radar or a camera) detects obstacles and reports them to the driver, except for light braking.
If the driver responds, it will help to increase the pressure on the pedal, if necessary.
If the driver does not react, even if the collision cannot be prevented, the device acts as intensively on the brake as possible and reduces the risk of damage to a minimum.
